ce:section.ce:para:
The chemical composition of N-GQDs has been investigated by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS). The survey spectrum (Fig. 3
                     a) shows strong C 1s, N 1s and O 1s peaks located at 284, 401 and 532 eV, respectively. By analyzing the high-resolution spectrum of C 1s (Fig. 3b), we discovered that there exist several types of carbon, including C–C/CC (284.4 eV), C–N (285.8 eV), C–O (286.5 eV), CO (288.2 eV) and OC–O (288.8 eV) [24]. Among them, the proportion of C–C/CC is ∼65.3%, which indicates that most carbon atoms formed a hexagonal structure with sp2 bonds [25]. Furthermore, the oxygen atoms mainly formed C–O bonds existed in the hydroxyl and epoxy groups as expected. The formation of these groups would not destroy the C–C/CC bonds of N-GQDs [30]. Thus a relatively intact honeycomb structure was maintained. It is worth nothing that the ratio of nitrogen atoms in N-GQDs is up to 18%. By analyzing the high resolution N 1s spectrum (Fig. 3c), the presences of amino-N/pyrrolic (399.5 eV, 31.5%), graphitic N (400.7 eV, 22.1%) and pyridine-N-oxide (406.6 eV, 46.4%) have been confirmed [6,31]. The content of N-dopants is up to ∼12.3% even after excluding the amino- and pyrrolic N at edges of the N-GQDs, which is higher than that reported in many publications (generally less than 10%) [24,32]. The high content of N-dopants may improve the chemical property and electronic transport of the GQDs. Interestingly, the pyridine-N-oxide is absent in nanocarbon hybrids as the raw materials, instead of the pyridinic N with comparable content of ∼43.6% (Table 1
                     ). It seems that the pyridinic N was changed into pyridine-N-oxide by reacting with free radicals (such as hydroxyl radicals) during the electrochemical process. Fig. 3d shows the scheme of the N-doped GQDs, which demonstrates its detailed configuration.

The optical properties of the N-GQDs are investigated in aqueous solution. The N-GQDs emits bright blue fluorescence excited by a 365 nm ultraviolet (UV) lamp (Fig. 4
                     a, inset). The blue fluorescence is probably generated from the zig-zag effect with a carbon-like triplet ground state of σ1π1 [34]. The UV–visible (UV–vis) spectrum of N-GQDs solution is shown in Fig. 4a. Two absorption peaks at 290 ​nm and 400 ​nm can be clearly seen, corresponding to the π-π* transition and n-π* transition, respectively. They are highly depending on the synthesis technique. In general, the GQDs obtained by electrochemical method have the absorption peak in the range of 250–300 ​nm [34]. In our case, the n-π* transition peak is located at 400 ​nm, which should be ascribed to the existence of N-dopants. PL 3D mapping of the N-GQDs solution is shown in Fig. 4b. The excitation wavelength is set in between 300 and 450 nm, and the emission wavelength is recorded from 350 nm to 550 nm. The red area represents the maximum fluorescence intensity, and the corresponded excitation/emission wavelength of the center of the area is ∼380 nm/∼450 nm. The normal PL spectra (Fig. 4c) show that the position and intensity of the emission peaks vary with the excitation wavelength. Specifically, the emission peaks red-shifted with increased intensity, when the excitation wavelength was tuned from 300 to 380 nm; By further increasing the wavelength to 450 nm, the peak intensity gradually decreased. The PL peak located at 455 nm has the strongest intensity excited at a wavelength of 380 nm. This is consistent with the PL 3D mapping (Fig. 4c). We also observed that the increase of electrolyte concentration led to the red-shift of the strongest emission peak (350 nm–390 nm) and the corresponding excitation wavelength (455 nm–466 nm) (Fig. S5, ESI). It should be attributed to the increase of –NH2 group at the edge of resulted N-GQDs. With increasing the current intensity, the strongest emission peak of N-GQDs excited at the wavelength of 370 nm blue-shifted (Fig. S6, ESI). The TEM images (Fig. S7，ESI) show that the morphology and size of N-GQDs have no significant change by varying the electrolyte concentration and current intensity. The PLQY of the N-GQDs (0.2 M, 0.01 A) is ∼19.3%, which is much higher than most of the GQDs synthesized by electrochemical method (Table 2
                     ). The high N-doping ratio is able to increase the crystallinity of the GQDs. Therefore, the defect states can be decreased, which should have benefited to the high PLQY of the N-GQDs [35].
